<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1868-10-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1868-10-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="516" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d516">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Hovey</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 95.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1868-10-01"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 1, 1868.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your dispatch of the 14th of September,
                            No. 147, has been received. It contains a very full and careful account
                            of the devastations which were produced in the republic of Ecuador, by
                            the terrible earthquake of the 13th of August. Losing no time in giving
                            publicity to the painful narrative, I sincerely hope that it may excite
                            not only the sympathies but the active charity of all the civilized
                            nations.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Alvin P. Hovey</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>